* {{Infobox shrine | name = '''Tenjin Shrine''' (天神神社) | image = Tenjin jinja2007-1.jpg | caption = Shrine approach | location = {{ill|Ikura, Mizuho|de|Ikura, Mizuho|ja|居倉|zh|居仓}}, {{ill|Mizuho|de|Mizuho|ja|瑞穂市|zh|瑞穗市}}, {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|de|Präfektur Gifu|ja|岐阜県|zh|岐阜县}}, Japan | coordinates = {{coord|35|25|20.8|N|136|38|37.4|E|display=inline,title}} | deity = {{ill|Takamimusubi|de|Takamimusubi|ja|タカミムスビ|zh|高皇産霊神|lt=Takamimusubi}} and {{ill|Kamimusubi|de|Kamimusubi|ja|カミムスビ|zh|神皇産霊神|lt=Kamimusubi}} | shrine_rank = Former village shrine | founded = Unknown | architecture = {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|de|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|zh|流建築|lt=Nagare style}} | alternate_name= | festival = {{ill|March 11|de|11. März|ja|3月11日|zh|3月11日}} | events = }}
'''Tenjin Shrine''' (天神神社) is a Shinto shrine located in Ikura, Mizuho, Gifu Prefecture, Japan. The shrine's former rank was a Village Shrine. It is believed to be the site of the Ikuragawa-no-miya ({{ill|Ikuragawa-no-miya|de|Ikuragawa-no-miya|ja|伊久良河宮|zh|伊久良河宫|lt=Ikura River Palace}}) where Princess {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|zh|倭姬命}} stayed, making it one of the Moto Ise Shrines.
==Deities==
{{ill|Takamimusubi|de|Takamimusubi|ja|タカミムスビ|zh|高皇産霊神}}
{{ill|Kamimusubi|de|Kamimusubi|ja|カミムスビ|zh|神皇産霊神}}
==History== According to the {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|ja|倭姫命世記|zh|倭姬命世记}}, in the 10th year of Emperor {{ill|Suinin|de|Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|zh|垂仁天皇}}, Princess {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|zh|倭姬命}} searched for a site to enshrine the {{ill|goshintai|de|goshintai|ja|御霊代|zh|御灵代}} of {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|de|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大神|zh|天照大神}}, traveling from Sakata-no-miya in {{ill|Omi Province|de|Provinz Ōmi|ja|淡海国|zh|淡海国}} to the Ikura River in {{ill|Mino Province|de|Provinz Mino|ja|美濃国|zh|美浓国}}. Legend holds that a palace was established here as the Ikuragawa-no-miya, and the stone known as the {{ill|Mifunashiro-ishi|de|Mifunashiro-ishi|ja|御船代石|zh|御船代石}} to the right of the main hall marks where her portable shrine was placed.Present-day Sakata Shinmei Shrine in Uga, Maibara, Shiga Prefecture: Sakata-no-miya reference. After four years, she departed to other sites along the river, eventually reaching the Nakashima-no-miya in present-day Ichinomiya.Potential sites include Sakemi Shrine and Sakate Shrine in present-day Ichinomiya.
Prior to the construction of a permanent shrine, the area was considered sacred ground, with rituals conducted around the Mifunashiro-ishi serving as an yorishiro. Archaeological finds around the stone include six {{ill|divine beast mirrors|de|Göttliche Tier-Spiegel|ja|神獣文鏡|zh|神兽文镜}} and over thirty {{ill|magatama|de|Magatama|ja|勾玉|zh|勾玉}} made of jade, indicating ancient ceremonial activity.
During the Edo period, the Aoki family of the {{ill|hatamoto|de|Hatamoto|ja|旗本|zh|旗本}} class patronized the shrine. The current main hall dates from a reconstruction in the Genroku era (1688–1704). Known previously as Ikuragawa-no-miya Tenjingū or Amatsujin Shrine, it was renamed Tenjin Shrine and designated a Village Shrine in 1873.
==Subsidiary Shrines== Two smaller shrines are located near the Mifunashiro-ishi, enshrining branch spirits of Ise Grand Shrine and Princess {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|zh|倭姬命}}.
==Cultural Properties==
Main hall of Tenjin Shrine (city-designated cultural property){{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=2708&shrname=%E2%98%85%E5%A4%A9%E7%A5%9E%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E2%98%85|title=Tenjin Shrine|publisher=Gifu Prefecture Shrine Agency|accessdate=2013-04-23}}
Site of Ikuragawa-no-miya (city-designated historic site){{Cite web|和書|date=2013-02-04|url=http://www.city.mizuho.lg.jp/mizuho/gaiyou/shizen/p-5679.html|title=Parks and Historic Sites|publisher=City of Mizuho|accessdate=2013-04-23}}
Tabunoki tree (city-designated natural monument)
==Location==
{{ill|Ikura|de|Ikura|ja|居倉|zh|居仓}}, {{ill|Mizuho|de|Mizuho|ja|瑞穂市|zh|瑞穗市}}, {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|de|Präfektur Gifu|ja|岐阜県|zh|岐阜县}} Surrounded by narrow winding roads; landmarks include Ikura Community Center and Nentoku-ji Temple.
==Access==
Approximately 30-minute walk from {{ill|Mieji Station|de|Mieji-Bahnhof|ja|美江寺駅|zh|美江寺站}} on the Tarumi Railway.
Take the Mizuho City community bus (Mizuho Bus) from {{ill|Hozumi Station|de|Hozumi-Bahnhof|ja|穂積駅|zh|穗积站}} on the Tōkaidō Main Line and alight at Ikura Community Center.
From the intersection of Gifu Prefectural Route 92 (Gifu–Sunami–Ōno Line) at Tanokami Akamiya, travel north approximately 1.5 km.
==Other== To the west stands the original tree of the Fuyu persimmon, one of the main varieties cultivated in the area, marked by a monument inscribed “Birthplace of the Fuyu Persimmon.”
