{{ill|Kamimusubi|de|Kamimusubi|ja|カミムスビ|zh|神皇産霊神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamimusubi|qq=}} [[ja:天神神社 (瑞穂市)]]
==History== According to the {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|ja|倭姫命世記|zh|倭姬命世记|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime-no-Mikoto Seiki|qq=}}, in the 10th year of Emperor {{ill|Suinin|de|Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|zh|垂仁天皇|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suinin|qq=}}, Princess {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|zh|倭姬命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|qq=}} searched for a site to enshrine the {{ill|goshintai|de|goshintai|ja|御霊代|zh|御灵代|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/goshintai|qq=}} of {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|de|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大神|zh|天照大神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=}}, traveling from Sakata-no-miya in {{ill|Omi Province|de|Provinz Ōmi|ja|淡海国|zh|淡海国|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Omi Province|qq=}} to the Ikura River in {{ill|Mino Province|de|Provinz Mino|ja|美濃国|zh|美浓国|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mino Province|qq=}}. Legend holds that a palace was established here as the Ikuragawa-no-miya, and the stone known as the {{ill|Mifunashiro-ishi|de|Mifunashiro-ishi|ja|御船代石|zh|御船代石|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mifunashiro-ishi|qq=}} to the right of the main hall marks where her portable shrine was placed.Present-day Sakata Shinmei Shrine in Uga, Maibara, Shiga Prefecture: Sakata-no-miya reference. After four years, she departed to other sites along the river, eventually reaching the Nakashima-no-miya in present-day Ichinomiya.Potential sites include Sakemi Shrine and Sakate Shrine in present-day Ichinomiya.
Prior to the construction of a permanent shrine, the area was considered sacred ground, with rituals conducted around the Mifunashiro-ishi serving as an yorishiro. Archaeological finds around the stone include six {{ill|divine beast mirrors|de|Göttliche Tier-Spiegel|ja|神獣文鏡|zh|神兽文镜|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/divine beast mirrors|qq=}} and over thirty {{ill|magatama|de|Magatama|ja|勾玉|zh|勾玉|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/magatama|qq=}} made of jade, indicating ancient ceremonial activity.
During the Edo period, the Aoki family of the {{ill|hatamoto|de|Hatamoto|ja|旗本|zh|旗本|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hatamoto|qq=}} class patronized the shrine. The current main hall dates from a reconstruction in the Genroku era (1688–1704). Known previously as Ikuragawa-no-miya Tenjingū or Amatsujin Shrine, it was renamed Tenjin Shrine and designated a Village Shrine in 1873.
==Subsidiary Shrines== Two smaller shrines are located near the Mifunashiro-ishi, enshrining branch spirits of Ise Grand Shrine and Princess {{ill|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|de|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|zh|倭姬命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|qq=}}.
==Cultural Properties==
Main hall of Tenjin Shrine (city-designated cultural property){{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=2708&shrname=%E2%98%85%E5%A4%A9%E7%A5%9E%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E2%98%85|title=Tenjin Shrine|publisher=Gifu Prefecture Shrine Agency|accessdate=2013-04-23}}
Site of Ikuragawa-no-miya (city-designated historic site){{Cite web|和書|date=2013-02-04|url=http://www.city.mizuho.lg.jp/mizuho/gaiyou/shizen/p-5679.html|title=Parks and Historic Sites|publisher=City of Mizuho|accessdate=2013-04-23}}
Tabunoki tree (city-designated natural monument)
==Location==
{{ill|Ikura|de|Ikura|ja|居倉|zh|居仓|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikura|qq=}}, {{ill|Mizuho|de|Mizuho|ja|瑞穂市|zh|瑞穗市|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mizuho|qq=}}, {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|de|Präfektur Gifu|ja|岐阜県|zh|岐阜县|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gifu Prefecture|qq=}} Surrounded by narrow winding roads; landmarks include Ikura Community Center and Nentoku-ji Temple.
==Access==
Approximately 30-minute walk from {{ill|Mieji Station|de|Mieji-Bahnhof|ja|美江寺駅|zh|美江寺站|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mieji Station|qq=}} on the Tarumi Railway.
Take the Mizuho City community bus (Mizuho Bus) from {{ill|Hozumi Station|de|Hozumi-Bahnhof|ja|穂積駅|zh|穗积站|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hozumi Station|qq=}} on the Tōkaidō Main Line and alight at Ikura Community Center.
From the intersection of Gifu Prefectural Route 92 (Gifu–Sunami–Ōno Line) at Tanokami Akamiya, travel north approximately 1.5 km.
==Other== To the west stands the original tree of the Fuyu persimmon, one of the main varieties cultivated in the area, marked by a monument inscribed “Birthplace of the Fuyu Persimmon.”
